HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1034
By McCalmon
A RESOLUTION to honor the memories of Aaron Stokes and
Austin Huskey of Williamson County.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were saddened to learn of the
untimely passings of Aaron Stokes and Austin Huskey of Williamson County; and
WHEREAS, Aaron Stokes and Austin Huskey were highly respected businessmen who
worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for their fellow citizens; and
WHEREAS, Aaron Stokes founded Shop Fix Academy in 2016 in Brentwood, an
endeavor that grew to a network of more than 1,500 independent auto repair shop owners and
is now based in Franklin; and
WHEREAS, the host of the radio show Fixin' Cars with Aaron Stokes, Mr. Stokes was
described as a mentor and entrepreneur who worked closely with independent shop owners;
and
WHEREAS, Austin Huskey was chief executive officer and the third-generation owner of
Franklin-based Huskey Truss & Building Supply; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Huskey was recognized as an LBM Journal 40 under 40 recipient in
2025, highlighting the value Aaron Huskey brought to his family's company and the building
supply industry; and
WHEREAS, Aaron Stokes and Austin Huskey leave behind indelible legacies of integrity
and probity in public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in
all their chosen endeavors; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memories of Aaron Stokes and Austin Huskey, reflecting
HJR1034
013639
- 1 -

fondly upon their impeccable character and stalwart commitment to living the examined life with
courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the families of Mr. Stokes and Mr. Huskey.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
